column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: I, John Vergis, was called at 0500 hrs. by the Wheeling and Lake Erie Brewster Yard Master about an odor that was coming from a cut of cars in the Brewster Yard.  When I arrived and walked the track, I discovered ice was starting to form on the bottom of the protective housing on tank car UTLX 957512.  When I investigated, I had found that the liquid valve on the B end was leaking.  The plug in the leaking valve along with the other two plugs in the other valves were less than hand tight.  I tried to tighten the valve handle on the leaking valve but when I did, the valve would turn on its own after a few seconds and reopen.  I tried this several times and got the same result.  I could not get the valve handle to stay closed.  I then tightened the plug in the leaking valve, and the leak stopped.  I also tightened the plugs in the other two valves.  The shipper has been notified and will be submitting a movement approval request to send to home shop.
column169: Better procedure needs to be followed when securing a car for transportation.

column168: On December 2nd, 2015 at 19:15 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered PROX 33383, a loaded tank car of UN 1075, LPG (Propane), was emitting a strong odor when near the tank car. The area was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-12-02-00292 was filed, shipper, Factor Gas Liquids, Inc., Ms. Valerie Kostyk, cellphone was notified of the incident. CSX Hazardous Material Systems Manager, Michael Bethge responded with EP+S of Vermont to investigate the release cause. The issue identified was product gas vapors bubbling from around the base plate mounting flange of the A-End liquid line to the manway pressure plate, the HazMat Mgr. tried to tighten the mounting stud nut, but the release was not stopped, therefore a Midland Capping Kit was applied, PROX 33383 was transferred on December 4th, 2015, and vapor flared to be Cleaned + Purged for Home Shop Dispo. The shipper, Factor Gas Liquids, Inc. was notified of the situation and assisted in obtaining a calf car for the transfer.      Cause Code: 270 (5 points)  NARRI:  5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: Request PROCOR Shop check land and groove gasket and stud nut torque on all valve mountings.

column168: On 12/03/2015 at 0530 hours, personnel in the CSXT Bennett Yard discovered RCRX 1115, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and (REAGENT CHEMICAL + RESEARCH, South Carolina Department of Health Environmental Control, National Response Center and CHEMTREC) were notified (CHEMTREC Report number 2015-1203-00049). HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the vapor line valve had all four nuts removed and three bolts removed from the valve. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Raymond Burnette. Contractor personnel replaced the bolts on the valve and conducted a bubble leak test and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code - 350 Air Inlet / Vapor Valve    5 (5 + 5 + 1) X (2 + 0) = 110

column168: Cargo tank motor vehicle was involved in a single vehicle rollover accident. As a result of the accident, the cargo tank received a single puncture of approximately a ¼ inch diameter on the side of the tank. It was approximately 1 hour before response personnel arrived. Spillage was puddled up, absorbent pads were put down to absorb the spillage and a dike built around spillage. Puddled spillage was vacuumed up while contents were pumped to another cargo tank. This process took approximately 4 hours until the cargo tank could be up-righted and the ¼ inch puncture was located. The puncture was plugged while the remainder of the contents transferred.  35 yards of impacted soil was excavated clean in accordance with Michigan DEQ requirements and removed from the site for disposal. The excavation was 7 ft. wide by 24 ft. long, by 4 ft. Deep and was filled in with 15 yards of sand and 20 yards of top soil.
column169: We will continue to train drivers in professional defensive driving techniques, Smith System and Cargo Tank Rollover prevention.  Future trucks we purchase will be equipped with the Wingman Fusion System that includes lane departure warnings.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 12/1/15, BNSF Carmen detected an odor coming from the ASOX 296039 during inspection.  The car was isolated and employees were removed from the area.  BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car and found that the liquid and vapor line plugs were both less than hand tight on the fittings.  Both valves were closed but vapor was seeping past the closed liquid line valve creating the odor.  The plugs were secured and tool tightened which stopped the release.  The car was isolated and shipper notified to work with the FRA to obtain an OTMA for further movement to offload and to shop for repair and inspection.  No liquid released from the car and the volume released is estimated based upon responder information and data.
column169: BNSF followed up with Americas Styrenics to provide details surrounding the release including lack of proper securement on the valve plugs.  The shipper should follow up with loading personnel to review correct procedures for tank car securement and to further review procedures for identifying failed components.

column168: Tank Car GATX 2815 was reported leaking in the railyard.  The responder reported the leak source was at GATX 2815 liquid valve secondary closure plug.  After inspection it was noted that the secondary closure plug was less than tool tight and had residual product from loading between the valve and secondary closure plug which resulted in product release.  The residual product was placed back into the car and the secondary closure plug was properly tool tightened.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank Car GATX 89329 was reported emanating vapors in the railyard.  The responder reported the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight.  The manway swing bolts were properly tool tightened which ended any further vapor release.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: Safety-Kleen Systems, Inc. operates a 10-day in-transit storage facility at 1525 W. Henrietta Road, Avon NY.  During the normal course of business, materials are brought to this location where they are temporarily stored pending continued transportation.  At approximately 3:00 AM on December 16, 2015 the facility’s fire alarm activated which was responded to by the Avon NY Fire Department.  Upon arrival, Fire Department Personnel gained access to the facility, identified three non-bulk polyethylene containers stored on a wooden pallet were smoldering/on fire and proceeded to extinguish the fire using both water and foam. Once the scene was under control, an emergency response crew  comprised of employees from both Safety-Kleen Systems and Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc initiated response activities which included the re-containerization of nearby containers impacted by water and firefighting foam, containerization of all clean-up debris including all firefighting water that was collected in a fully contained secondary confinement unit and decontamination/cleaning of all impacted surfaces. All materials generated as a result of the response activities were disposed of at a fully licensed waste management facility. It is important to note that the storage location where the incident occurred was designed for the storage of hazardous material/hazardous waste and is within a sealed secondary containment unit. There were no waterways impacted as a result of the initial fire or firefighting activities.
column169: At the conclusion of the response activities, an internal investigation was initiated to determine the materials involved and the suspected cause of the incident. The investigation revealed that a field crew had packaged multiple 1-gallon containers of unused, unopened and outdated Organic Peroxide Type D liquids into polyethylene non-bulk packages for the purpose of transportation and disposal using vermiculite to for cushioning. At the time the material was prepared for transportation the individual containers were inspected and found to be in shippable condition. During the course of transportation, the containers were off-loaded into a warehouse pending continued transportation. Prior to the incident, a routine facility inspection was conducted and the containers appeared normal. The shipper of the material was contacted and we confirmed that the material offered for transportation and disposal was outdated material that had never been opened. The Safety Data Sheet was reviewed and the material was not exposed to any listed incompatible materials or had been subjected to temperatures in excess of the documented self-accelerating decomposition temperatures of 60 degrees Celsius (140 degrees Fahrenheit).    Our investigation was not able to identify the cause of the incident but will continue to insure that all material prepared for transportation are done so in full compliance with all applicable rules and regulations. In addition, deviations from our established protocols if identified will be investigated and appropriate corrective actions taken to ensure compliance going forward.    Our investigation was not able to identify the cause of the incident but will continue to insure that all material prepared for transportation are done so in full compliance with all applicable rules and regulations. In addition, deviations from our established protocols if identified will be investigated and appropriate corrective actions taken to ensure compliance going forward.

column168: THE SULFURIC ACID TANKER ARRIVED 2 DAYS AHEAD OF SCHEDULE. THE LAB TECH IN CHARGE OF OFFLOADING THE TANKER DID THE CALCULATIONS FOR AVAILABLE SPACE IN THE TANKER AND BEGAN THE OFFLOAD. THE USE-ABLE VOLUME OF THE 20K GALLON TANK WAS ACTUALLY 19.3K GALLONS. AT THE VERY END OF THE OFFLOAD, A STRONG ACID SMELL WAS NOTICED AROUND THE TANK. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE TANK HAD OVERFLOWED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGEMENT TEAM WAS BROUGHT IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. AFTER THE ACID WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA A CONTAINMENT DRAIN VALVE WAS FOUND OPEN THAT HAD ALLOWED 275 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID TO ESCAPE TO AN ON SITE HOLDING POND. THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE WYOMING  DEQ.
column169: TANK VOLUME CALCULATIONS WILL BE ADJUSTED TO ACCOUNT FOR THE ACTUAL TANK VOLUME. THE CONTROL VALVE WAS CLOSED AND SHALL REMAIN IN THE NORMALLY CLOSED POSITION GOING FORWARD TO ENSURE THERE WILL BE NO MORE SPILLS THAT WILL LEAVE THE CONTAINMENT AREA. LAB TECHNICIANS HAVE RECEIVED ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON TANKER OFFLOAD PROCEDURES.

column168: THE BOX WAS FOUND WITH WET SAGGING BOTTOM FLAPS. THE BOX WAS OPENED TO DETERMINE IF THE INNER CONTENTS HAD SPILLED. UPON EXAMINING THE CONTENTS, SEVERAL BAGS OF DRY ICE WERE FOUND. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING INDICATING THE CONTENTS CONTAINED A REGULATED MATERIAL. AS THERE WAS A REASONABLE EXPECTATION THAT THE DRY ICE WOULD SUBLIMATE PRIOR TO AN FAA INSPECTION, I ORDERED LOCAL FEDEX PERSONNEL TO TAKE DIGITAL PICTURES OF ALL SIX SIDES OF THE BOX AND CONTENTS. I FORWARDED THOSE PICTURES DURING A TELEPHONIC NOTIFICATION TO HAZMAT MANAGER BRYAN BUCHANAN, DFW SECFO. THE FREIGHT WAS RELEASED TO ENSURE THE FOODSTUFFS BEING COOLED BY THE DRY ICE DID NOT SPOIL.

column168: (1) 55 gallon drum was loaded onto a faulty pallet by the shipper. It was punctured by a nail and released approximately 1 cup of material onto the trailer floor. The duration of this release was immediate. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release.

During offloading operations it was discovered that a 350 gallon metal tote was leaking from a cracked weld/seam joint where the tote and the piping meet resulting in the release of approximately 2 liquid gallons to the wooden freight trailer and adjacent concrete dock floor only. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by this release. An environmental contractor was dispatched and transferred the product into metal drums (as per the shipper's instructions) Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted areas. The damaged tote and drums with transferred product were staged on site pending the shipper's disposition. All wastes were collected, containerized and staged on site for pending disposal

column168: A box of UN1263 Paint, 3, II was found to be crushed during unloading at the R&L terminal in Kennesaw, GA. One can within the box was damaged and leaking. The release was immediate. An environmental contractor conducted over pack and clean-up operations. This is considered a one-time incident.

On December 28, 2015 terminal personnel loaded a box containing 4-1 gallon containers or UN1824, ET Ultra Klene, upside down and then pulled the box out and dropped it on the dock. Approximately 1 gallon immediately leaked from the containers to the box itself. Contractor solidified the release into a 55 gallon drum along with the debris to be taken for disposal.

A 5-gallon pail of UN3264 Corrosive Liquid was punctured by a forklift during unloading at the XPO Logistics terminal. The release was immediate and was contained to the trailer floor. column169: This valve was not one the drivers normally use and was out of immediate visibility. I will add that we had an additional 2 other non-hazardous spills recently from the same valve so we have now sent out a fleet message to create awareness on the topic.  If this trend continues we will pursue additional training venues.

column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING HYDROCHLORIC ACID 31% TO HASA. THE DRIVER OPENED UP HIS VALVES AND TURNED ON HIS PUMP TO BEGIN FILLING THE CUSTOMER’S TANK. DURING THE FILL THE DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF HIS TRAILS. HE THEN SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSED THE VALVE TO STOP THE LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON LEAKED TO THE PAVEMENT. THE HCL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE TO A PH LEVEL OF 7. THE CUSTOMER AND DRIVER CLEANED UP THE SPILL TO THE CUSTOMER’S SATISFACTION. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION A 1’ CRACK WAS FOUND ON THE FLANGE OF THE OFFLOAD SPOUT SUPPORT BRACKET ON TOP OF THE TRAILER. THE CRACK ALLOWED THE HCL TO LEAK.
column169: THE TRAILER INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS SENT TO THE SHOP TO REPAIR THE FLANGE. MOVING FORWARD THE DRIVER WILL DO A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE FLANGE BEFORE OFFLOADING.

On 12/10/15 at 1209 hours it was reported in the CSXT Montgomery located in Montgomery, AL, discovered NATX77196, a loaded tank car of Nitrobenzene to be leaking from the liquid line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, First Chemical Corp (C/o Chemours), was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and secured the leak.  It was discovered that the liquid line ball valve (screw on type ball valve) was found to be loose.  The source of the leak was found to be coming from the bottom of the liquid line valve.  Hepaco tightened the liquid line ball valve securing the leak.  It was also discovered that the protective housing pin was broken. These actions were communicated to the shipper (Barry Lindley, Chemours). Chemours contracted ResCar to respond.  ResCar responded on 12/14/15, secured the liquid valve, repaired the protective housing pin, and conducted a pressure test with a passing level. The car was released upon completion of the passing pressure test and repairs made by ResCar. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 282- Liquid Line/ Liquid Valve Threaded Valve less than tool tight    5(5+3+5) x (2+0) = 130 NARRI         Montgomery, AL  12/10/15  NATX77196  Nitrobenzene
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 12/14/15 at 1915 hours it was reported in the CSXT Boyles Yard located in Birmingham (Tarrant), AL a discovered AZXX32014, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine, Alpha-Pinene to be leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, International Paper, was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and secured the leak.  It was discovered that the manway gasket was kinked and deteriorated. Hepaco replaced the manway gasket and secured the car. These actions were communicated to the shipper (Randell Maull). The car was secured, re-sealed, and released. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 209- Manway Hinged/ Bolt, Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover, gasket deteriorated    5(5+3+3) x (2+4) = 330 NARRI         Birmingham (Tarrant), AL  12/14/2015  AZXX32014  Crude Sulfate Turpentine, Alpha-Pinene

column168: On 14 December 2015, FRA HM Inspector Anthony Schneider took exception to tank car HOKX112358 in the CSX Collinwood Yard, Cleveland, OH. Upon notification from HM Inspector Schneider, all necessary shipper and regulatory notifications were made. Specialized Professional Services, Inc from Canton, OH was contracted to respond, investigate, and secure the tank car.     SPSI's investigation revealed the top mounted exterior pressure relief device was secured via a 4 bolt flange - this flange was welded to the top of the car in an apparent historical retrofit. The welded connection between the riser and the tank was cracked, resulting in the release of material during transportation. Due to recent rain event, the moisture on the top of the car adjacent to the pressure relief device was inspected with colometric pH paper, and confirmed the presence of an alkaline material consistent with the registered material being transported in the tank car. The tank car was wiped free from moisture / product, and testing was performed on standing water adjacent to the car on the tracks - confirming no release to the ground. A temporary patch using a commercial plugging compound was used to prevent any further release.    On 14 December 2015 Joseph Taylor, Manager Hazardous Materials CSX Transportation contacted Kevin Blackwell, FRA Hazardous Materials Washington, DC and was given permission to have the car moved from its standing position in the yard, to the adjacent facility - consignee. This move was conducted on 15 December 2015 without further release and the car is to be offloaded, cleaned + purged, and necessary repairs made.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On December 17, 2015, at 1224 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Avon Terminal, Avon, Indiana reported that a GAMX 6516, a loaded tank car of UN1993, WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. was leaking from the top of the tank car. Reportedly, there was product around the manway with no impact to the ground. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Stericycle care of Petro-Chem Processing Group, was notified via emergency number 877-577-2669. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. Summit found that the manway gasket was deteriorated and cracked but all manway bolts were appropriately tool tight. The shipper representative, MELANIE FROHRIEP, was notified of the situation found. GAMX 6516 was released after a new manway gasket was installed and the tank car was properly secured for transportation. This incident did require a special move.  NARRI: 5x(5+3+1)x(2+0) = 90  Cause code:209  Manifest number: 014099163JJK
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 12/21/2015 at 1708 hours personnel in  CSXT Bennett Yard  discovered GATX 69869, a loaded tank car of Ethylene Glycol leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and DAK America, South Carolina DHEC, NRC, and CHEMTREC were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2015-12-21-00180 ). Daniel Hastings (HEPACO) a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one of four bolts on the liquid line flange was less than tool tight, and the manway did not have a manway gasket applied. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Gary Singleton. Contractor personnel fixed the problem and decontaminated the. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 284 Liquid Line / Pipe flange bolts/nut less than tool tight                                   207 Manway, hinged and bolted / gasket missing    5(3+1+0) x (2+0) = 40 NARRI

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY AT 04:30 AM ON DECEMBER 11, 2015 I NOTICED THE MORNING RESPONSIBLE MANAGEMENT PERSON (RMP) CARRYING A SMOKING PACKAGE WALKING TOWARDS THE OUTSIDE DOOR. THE PACKAGE WAS NOT ON FIRE BUT RATHER WAS EMITTING VISIBLE SMOKE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ITEM, MAC TOOLS JUMP-N-CARRY BATTERY CHARGER/JUMPSTART DEVICE. THE LEADS WHICH WERE PROTRUDING FROM THE BOX AND EVENTUALLY CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE SIDE OF THE BOXLINE CAGE (METAL) CAUSING THE LEADS TO HEAT WHICH PRODUCED PACKAGING TO ENSURE THAT NO OTHER METAL WOULD CONTACT THE LEADS. THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND SECURED FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THIS UNIT IS BELIEVED TO BE POWERED BY A 12 VOLT SEALED LEAD ACID BATTERY (BASED UPON INTERNET RESEARCH).

column18: 8 MILES WEST OF HUNTINGTON, UTAH ON SR 3
column163: 8 Miles West of Huntington, Utah on SR 3
column168: At 16:00 a failed latching mechanism on the tail gate of a dump truck resulted in the spill of approximately 1000 lbs. of wet bituminous coal ash. The ash was being dredged from a pond on property site and transported with dump trucks approximately 4.3 miles to the on site ash landfill for final disposal. Approximately 1.25 miles of this route was along Utah State Road 31. The spill started on a gravel road and extended onto approximately 100 yards of the asphalt surface of Utah SR 31. As soon as the driver noticed the failed tailgate, he pulled to the side of the road effectively mitigating any more spillage. The spill was reported to the on-shift supervisor at 16:30 and then to the PacifiCorp internal spill hotline @ 16:47. At 17:05, the spill was reported to the State of Utah Division Environmental Response and Remediation. Clean-up activities included scooping up the ash on the road with a front end loader and cleaning the highway with a street sweeper. The Utah Highway Patrol assisted with the after-hours clean-up by providing with traffic control. The road remained open during the entire clean-up procedure. Final clean-up took place during the morning hours of 12/10/2015.
column169: The contractor that was hired to provide the dredging and ash removal services took the faulty dump truck off site for repair. In the future, better attention to the maintenance and working condition of the tailgates would prevent a reoccurrence of this event from happening again.

column168: THIS INCIDENT DID NOT INVOLVE A FAILURE ON ANY PORTION OF OUR BOBTAIL CARGO TANK NOR ITS DISTRIBUTION/DISCHARGE SYSTEM. THE CARGO WAS NOT IN TRANSPORTATION ON A HIGHWAY AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE INVOLVED A STATIONARY 1000 GALLON ASME TANK THAT IS PART OF A PROPANE LIQUID DISPENSING STATION AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION. THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF THE CUSTOMER UNINTENTIONALLY LEAVING A HOSE-END VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION ON THE DISPENSING EQUIPMENT. AS WE WERE TRANSFERRING PROPANE FROM OUR BOBTAIL INTO THIS STATIONARY CONTAINER, THE RELEASE OCCURRED FROM THE OPEN HOSE-END VALVE. THE CUSTOMER’S EMPLOYEE ALSO DID NOT CLOSE A MAIN VALVE THAT CONTROLS THE FLOW OF LIQUID PROPANE FROM THE STATIONARY 1000 GALLON TANK. THIS IS STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE. WE ARE PROVIDING ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO THIS CUSTOMER SO THAT THEY CAN SAFELY OPERATE THIS DISPENSING SYSTEM IN THE FUTURE. NO PORTION OF OUR CARGO TANK’S DISTRIBUTION/DISCHARGE SYSTEM WAS INVOLVED IN THIS RELEASE. OUR BOBTAIL WAS PARKED AT THE CUSTOMER SITE TO PUMP PROPANE IN TO THE STATIONARY TANK. SO OUR CARGO WAS NOT IN TRANSIT. THE LIQUID PUMPING SYSTEM CONNECTED TO THE 1000 GALLON TANK DID NOT FAIL. THE 1000 GALLON ASME STATIONARY CONTAINER DID NOT FAIL. THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSE BY HUMAN ERROR.     WE STILL WANTED TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT BECAUSE IT CAUSED A HIGHWAY TO BE SHUT DOWN AND SOME MINOR EVACUATIONS TO OCCUR- AND RELEASE OCCURRED WHILE WE WERE IN THE PRODUCT TRANSFER PROCESS FROM OUR CARGO TANK TRUCK. WE DID ATTEMPT TO NOTIFY THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER BY TELEPHONE ABOUT 8:00PM EST ON THE DAY OF THE EVENT. WE PHONED A NUMBER OF TIMES BUT RECEIVED A BUSY SIGNAL ON (800) 424-8802.
column169: TRAINING HAD BEEN PREVIOUS CONDUCTED FOR THE EMPLOYEES OF THIS CUSTOMER, AND WE ARE PROVIDING ADDITIONAL TRAINING SO THAT THE CUSTOMER’S EMPLOYEES CAN CONDUCT THIS PROCESS SAFELY IN THE FUTURE.

column168: The driver opened a small valve located inside the catch basin at the connection point on the loading line to bleed off line pressure before hooking to load. After connecting the loading hose, the driver failed to close the valve. Once loading began, the catch basin filled with product and began overflowing onto the ground. The driver had stepped away from the connection point unaware of the situation. Upon returning to the connection point a few minutes later and realizing the situation, the driver shut down all loading processes. The driver then closed the valve inside the catch basin, built dams to secure the spilled product, contacted management, and began cleaning up the spilled product using items from the spill kit located on his equipment. The product was absorbed by utilizing medium density absorption pads. Afterwards, Oil gator micro bug was applied to and rake into the soil surface to help assist the remediation process and further absorption of product. The affected area was located on the clay, gravel soil surface immediately surrounding the catch basin at the loading head and a small portion of the loading area. It continued along the ground down into two clay soil bottomed vehicle track furrows that led to the loading point. The product lightly covered the surface in an area approximately ten feet wide by ten feet long up to the furrows. It then split lightly filling the furrows, which were approximately fourteen to eighteen inches wide, for approximate fifty feet. The product was maintained inside the furrows until removed. The area will continue to be monitored for a period long enough to comfortably feel all product has sufficiently been absorbed. This will include any periods of precipitation. The affected soil will the ben removed and replaced.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HOTLINE WAS CONTACTED AT THE TIME OF NOTIFICATION (INCIDENT NUMBER 15-05009)
column169: This is a rare occurrence for this driver, the procedures currently in place are sufficient to prevent spills when followed. This driver failed to follow all of the procedures carefully, we expect the driver to follow the procedures in place which state he is not allowed to be more than ten feel from the loading point.

column162: DIRECTOR OF OPERATING RULES AND SAFETY
column168: During a walking inspecting of their train, the conductor noticed the sides of tank car cbtx 743414 appeared wet and in addition they reported a very noticeable smell of ethanol. The crew member at once notified the train dispatcher and the car was isolated until the railroads environmental response arrived (the shipper and customer were also notified). Upon arrival, the railroads contracted response (Moran environmental recovery) assessed the car (including fittings and securements) there was no obvious location where the product had likely escaped. Further testing included moving the car with a locomotive in order to determine a leak point. This also resulted with no leak observed, however there was a very noticeable smell of ethanol and to repair the problem. On 12/23 a rescue crew arrived to affect repairs and release the car for normal service. The rescue crew replaced (with new seals) the manway and multi-housing gaskets. They stated that the car also looked to be "very full" with only about eight to ten inches of air space above the product. Once the repairs were completed, the care was moved to the worcester scale track and weighed, the car was again inspected and then released for normal service.
column169: It appears that the manway gaskets had become brittle breaking apart are the repairs crew removed it; this appears to have allowed a small amount product seepage and vapors to escape. From my perspective and with the cars age only being one year old. The degradation of the gaskets integrity seems premature.

column168: THIS LETTER IS TO SEVER AS THE OFFICIAL INCIDENT SUMMARY FOR THE TRAILER FIRE ON 12/2/2015. ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS INC WAS TRANSPORTING 29 DRUMS AND 7 PALLETS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE ALONG WITH SOME NON HAZARDOUS WASTES TO EWS LOCATED IN ALABAMA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE RED LIGHT ON ROUTE 220 IN FRONT OF THE HOME DEPORT HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE TRAILER. HE PULLED OFF IMMEDIATELY AND CALLED 911 THEN OUR OFFICE. THE ROANOKE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED ALONG WITH WELL TO HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP. LEANN HERMAN CALLED THE ROANOKE DEQ OFFICE AND SPOKE TO KIMBERLEY THOMPSON TO MAKE AN INITIAL NOTIFICATION AND ALSO REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE NRC. MS HERMAN SPOKE TO MS RAWLS WITH THE NRC AND WAS GIVEN 1134788 AS THE INCIDENT REPORT NUMBER.    ALL DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS REPACKED ONSITE AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER EO TRAILER. NONE OF THE WASTE WAS SENT TO EQS THAT NIGHT. IT ALL CAME BACK TO EO IN ROCKY MOUNT VA. MS. HERMAN FILED A TEN DAY EXTENSION WITH THE DEQ OFFICE FOR THIS MATERIAL. THE EXTENSION LETTER IS ATTACHED.     THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT IN THE CLEAN UP WILL BE TESTED FOR PROPER WASTE CLASSIFICATION AND WILL BE SHIPPED OFF FOR PROPER DISPOSAL UNDER ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS.
column169: ENVIRONMENTAL WILL NOT PICK UP ANY MATERIAL FROM ECOLAB UNLESS OUR TECHNICIAN HAS PACKED THE MATERIAL FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING A TRUCK TRACTOR SEMI TRAILER WITH A T-11 UN PORTABLE TANK. THE SEMI TRAILER OVER TURN ONTO IT'S SIDE, DURING A LOW SPEED MANEUVER, DUE TO HYDRAULIC FORCES OF LIQUID SLOSH. THE TANK CAME TO REST ON IT'S SIDE AND THEN BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE MAN HOLE COVER, THE WING NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK SLOWED, THE PLEXSURF 210 E/S-220 WAS CAUGHT IN CONTAINMENT. FIVE GALLONS OF PLEXSURF 210 E/S-220 WAS RELEASED DURING THE INCIDENT. THE TANK WAS RIGHTED AND THE PLEXSURF WAS OFF LOADED INTO A REPLACEMENT TANK AND THE CONTAINER WAS HAULED AWAY. ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOAK UP THE SPILLED SLEXURF AND WAS PROPERLY REMOVED.     THE INCIDENT HAPPENED AT 193 AND THE TANK RIGHTED AT 0200.

column17: Reclaimed Energy Div., Superior Oil Co., Inc.
column168: a shipment of 8 drums was received on non regulated manifest dated 12/21/2015. Upon analysis, it was discovered that 3 of the 8 drums had a flashpoint below 140F causing the material to be hazardous waste.  No material was released.

A trailer unloading 1 gal poly pails of UN1760 corrosive cleaning solution reported a 1 gal release due to improper bracing for transport. The spill was cleaned up by terminal personnel and placed into a 5 gal poly pail for the terminal to manage.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A trailer unloading a 35 gal steel drum of UN1993 flammable liquid reported a 2 gal release on the dock floor due to a pallet nail puncturing the base of the drum. Contractors were dispatched to assist in cleanup and overpacking.

During unloading activities a 275 gallon poly tote of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide at the customer location reported a 5 oz release on the top of the tote due to a defective cap. Apparently the threading in the cap was damaged causing the release during transit. A contractor was dispatched to assist in cleanup and replace the damaged cap.

During unloading activities at the terminal, a 1 gal poly pail of UN2922 corrosive metalworking fluid inside a cardboard box reported a spill which occurred during transit due to improper bracing. The spill was contained within the box and terminal personnel over packed all waste into a 5 gal poly pail and staged onsite pending shipper instructions.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: On December 31, 2015, terminal personnel discovered 1-50 lbs bag of UN3378, Green Clean Pro damaged while unloading the trailer. The 50 lbs bag was damaged at a previous terminal due to improper loading. Approximately 2 lbs of product was immediately released to the trailer floor. Contractor cleaned the released and placed the damaged bag and spilled product into a 8 gallon drum to be taken offsite for disposal.

On December 17, 2015, terminal personnel discovered 1-55 gallon drum on UN1294, Toluene DR400 Resin to be damaged while unloading a trailer. Approximately 55 gallons of product was released to the trailer floor from being punctured by a forklift during loading. Contractor used absorbent materials to collect and containerize the release. Contractor then power washed the trailer. Contractor generated 1-85 gallon drum of the damaged drum, 5-55 gallon drums of cleanup debris and rinse water to be taken offsite pending disposal.

A single 55-gallon steel drum of UN1866 Resin Solution was damaged by a forklift during loading operations. The damage was not discovered until off-loading at the customer location in Stockton, CA. The released material was cleaned by an environmental contractor and the damaged drum was overpacked and disposed of in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.

column168: (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1263 Valspar Off White Backer was punctured by a forklift during loading operations at a R+L Carriers shipping terminal in Portland, OR. Approximately 1 gallon of material was released inside the trailer and onto the concrete dock. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. The duration of the release was immediate. Terminal personnel cleaned the release.

(1) 55-gallon steel drum of UN1274 Propyl Alcohol was found with a leaking seam at the bottom of the drum at an R+L Carriers shipping terminal. Approximately 2 ounces were released onto the cardboard beneath the drum inside the trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. The duration of this release was during transit. Terminal personnel cleaned the release.

(1) 275 gallon poly tote containing UN3264 Iridite 14-6L was found leaking when it arrived at the XPO Logistics shipping terminal. Approximately 3 ounces were released from a loose cap on the top of the tote. The release was confined to the top of the tote. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. The duration of this release was during transit. The tote was wiped down and the cap was tightened.

(1) 55 gallon steel drum containing UN1133 M-479 was punctured by a forklift during loading. Approximately 3 gallons was released inside the trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release. The duration of the release was immediate. The drum was over packed and staged on site pending shipper instructions.

column168: Approximately 1 gallon of UN1263 "Deltron 2000 B/C Black Mixing Base" released from a 1 gallon metal can that was crushed by an adjacent pallet during loading activities. The release impacted the floor of the trailer and was confined to the inside of the trailer. Terminal personnel cleaned the release with absorbents and containerized the damaged container and waste into an 8 gallon drum.

Consignee reported to shipper and HTC Terminal Manager that material had leaked into crash box/dome area. Consignee cleaned up release and unloaded trailer with further issues.   Empty trailer was transported to carrier terminal, cleaned and inspected. Carrier found the following defect.  Defective vacuum vent, O ring failed. At some point an encapsulated Teflon O ring had been replaced with an O ring made of a different material. Vacuum vent was replaced.

column168: On December 9, 2015 at approximately 18:00, our tractor trailer was traveling north on i-59 passing the arkadelphia on-ramp with an averitt tractor trailer in the lane to his left and an unidentified tractor trailer merging onto the interstate to his right. The unidentified tractor trailer immediately moved into our drivers’ lane squeezing him between the two tractor trailers.   Our drivers’ reaction was to apply full braking to avoid multiple collisions with the two tractor trailers and/or traffic. The driver then moved his tractor trailer to the emergency lane, exited the truck, observed a release and notified authorities via the 911 call center.     It is assumed that the hard braking action caused some object to puncture one or more hydrogen peroxide containers resulting in the release.  Furthermore, an interaction between the hydrogen peroxide and wood pallets from other product onboard caused an exothermic reaction and subsequent fire. The release lasted approximately 4 ½ hours.    #1: the fire melted the hydrogen peroxide container causing vaporization of product.  #2: the fire destroyed the copper sulfate containers burning and vaporizing the product.  #3: the fire melted the sulfuric acid container causing vaporization of the product.  #4: the fire caused excessive pressure in the toleune container causing an explosion and vaporization of product.  #5: the fire melted the sodium hydroxide containers causing vaporization of the product.  #6: the fire partially melted multiple sodium bisulfite containers causing vaporization of the product.  The fire department was on-site to direct initial response activities. Sand was brought in and strategically placed in an adjacent concrete drainage ditch to prevent runoff from the site. Sodium bicarbonate was applied to neutralize and solidify runoff. Foam was applied to the trailer to contain and suppress the fire. An environmental response contractor was on-site to conduct clean-up and restoration activities.
column169: Upon review of loading procedures, all were found to be adequate. Management will continue to investigate the incident and implement modifications when appropriate.  Note: it is believed that damage to this product initiated the loss of other product onboard, caused the destruction of the trailer and prompted remediation of the site. Therefore, total carrier damage cost and remediation cost are included on this report only. Cost of material loss is included on each subsequent report for the material/package involved.    #1 #2 #3 #4 #5 #6: upon review of loading procedures, all were found to be adequate.    Management will continue to investigate the incident and implement modifications when appropriate.

column168: During the air sort (between approximately 5 p.m., and 6:15 p.m.) a large package came through the air dock that had a visible layer of frost forming along the bottom edge. As this is usually a sign of dry ice, a supervisor performed and investigation of the contents. The contents were determined to be several packages of dry ice inside of plastic baggies with the class 9miscellaneous diamond hazard label and un 1845 printed on them, interspersed between bags of "primal patties, duck formula dog food". There were no outer markings to show that the shipment contained dry ice.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0200, ON DECEMBER 16, 2015, RESPONDER WAS CONTACTED BY RADIO BY THE UNLOAD 1 PART-TIME SUPERVISOR. HE REPORTED A HAZMAT LEAKER HAD BEEN DISCOVERED IN BAY DOOR 4. WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE, RESPONDER WENT TO THE LOCATION WITH THE SPILL CART. UPON ARRIVAL, A 15' RADIUS WAS CLEARED. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE HAZMAT WAS INDEED LEAKING AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN CONTAMINATED. USING THE DECISION TREE, PROPER CLEAN-UP OF THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS DONE, AND THE LEAKING BOX WAS SECURELY PLACED IN A SPILL TRAY AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING.
column169: UPON INSPECTION, THE CAP WAS NOT TIGHTLY SECURED ON THE BOTTLE. BEFORE SHIPMENT, CAPS SHOULD BE SECURED TIGHTLY AND TAPED TO PREVENT THEM FROM COMING LOOSE DURING TRANSPORT.

column168: WET PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON THE MISSORT SLIDE OF THE PURPLE BELT. A HAZMAT RESPONDER PLACED THE HAZMAT PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TUB AND TRANSPORTED IT TO THE DMP. HE USED HIS DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID TO HANDLE THE PACKAGE. IT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN THE DMP USING THE CHART FOR DISPOSAL IN A FULL DMP FACILITY FOUND IN THE DECISION TREE.

column168: Supervisor, tariq zaman1, was moving a hazmat package to the truck @ door 1418 when he noticed it was leaking. He put the package back on the irreg. cart & notified the designated responders. When I arrived to the area, i utilized my decision tree/response sheets to access the situation. Because the package was corrosive, i altered my PPE to include the silver shield inner liners. I tested the PH of the liquid. I moved the package to a lined spill tray & then neutralized it with sodium bicarbonate. I used clay-based absorbent to solidify any remaining liquid. I swept up all contaminated materials & added them to the spill tray. I then took the package to the DMP area for further processing. When i open the box, i found that one of the bottles had cracked.

The spilled material was cleaned up with granular absorbents and properly disposed of.  The contents of the damaged tote was transferred to a new poly tote.  Which continued on for shipping.

column168: An estimated three (3) gallons of UN1263, Gold Enamel paint was released from a CMTV due to mechanical pump failure. The response contractor remained on site during the remainder of the offload of approximately 200 gallons. The release duration was immediate.

column168: During this event, a CTMV released 0.5 gallons of product to adjacent limestone gravel while exiting the destination facility. This release occurred due to a mechanical failure of the internal valve gasket allowing the product to impact a 12 foot x 3 foot area of limestone gravel. Upon noticing the release the driver immediately capped the external valve. An outside emergency response contractor was contacted by the Carrier to respond to neutralize and remediate impacted gravel.  Based on the quantity released, the duration of the release was within one minute. Our Event No. is 49187

Approximately 12 oz. of UN1293 Triethylamine released from a 55 gallon drum that was punctured by a forklift blade. The release impacted the floor of a trailer. The drum was turned on its side to stop the leak. Terminal personnel applied absorbents to the trailer floor and the trailer has departed the terminal. A contractor responded, cleaned the release, and over packed the damaged drum. All waste was containerized for disposal.

The tanker was overfilled by operator.  As waste began coming out of the rear dome of the tanker, the pump was immediately shut off.  Operator began putting down spill pads so as to contain the 100 gallon spill.  In house emergency response team was assembled and cleaned without incident.  All clean-up debris and materials used were collected and placed into a suitable package.
column169: A thorough and comprehensive review of the incident was immediately reviewed with Clean Harbors and Safety Kleen.  Findings show the root cause of the incident was ultimately operator error.  The driver will receive retraining in tank operation. A review of policy at our receiving facilty has been completed; new SOPs have been implemented so as to ensure loading and unloading procedures will be monitered at all times.   Additionally all drivers entering the facility will be required to receive training at each 6-month interval.

column168: AWB 006 5017 7793 originated in CLE via DTW to LAX. Frt was not screened prior to arrival here in DTW via Forward Air. The air waybill reflected Metal Detectors. I was present along with 1 of the prospect screeners during this time and conducted the physical search. Each of us open separate boxes at which time I noticed a piece inside stated battery pack and the paperwork inside stated .8Ah battery. There are 6 boxes that have these batteries backup kits with that include paperwork that reflect .8Ah battery inside. No other paperwork was provided. No labels marked on outside of boxes reflecting DG.

column168: Prior to the incident, the CTMV had a double tire blowout at speed, which was repaired and the CTMV was pre-tripped. A contractor was dispatched to clean up the released material, and assist in trans loading the material. The duration of the release was approximately four hours. column168: Reported that (2) 55 gallon steel drums of Valspar 86X066B GLD DSPRSN UN1263 Paint, Class 3, PG III were accidentally punctured by a forklift on the terminal dock. The (2) punctured 55 gallon drums released a combined 3 gallons of material onto the concrete terminal floor. The drums were flipped over once the leaks were discovered and the spill was contained. The contractor over packed the (2) 55 gallon drums and left them onsite for OS&D. No waterways, soils, or drains were impacted by the release.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10 AM ON DECEMBER 28, 2015, KATHY KEYS RECEIVED CAPPING B SOLUTION IN THREE 204L CONTAINERS. AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30AM RAY OSOWSKI ASKED JULLEON TO MONITOR THE AREA. THE CONTAINERS WERE MOVED OUTSIDE, VENTED, AND CLEANED. PEOPLE WERE ALLOWED BACK INTO THE BUILDING AT 12:10PM.

column168: THE FLANGE LEADING TO THE WELL PIPE ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER HAD BECOME LOOSE SINCE IT WAS MANUFACTURED IN FEBRUARY 2015. UNIT WAS NOT DUE FOR ANNUAL MAINTENANCE. THE SLOSHING OF THE LIQUID CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT TO SEEP OUT IN TO THE MANWAY AND FALL TO THE GROUND VIA THE DRAIN AS THE DRIVER WAITED ON W BRADLEY TO ENTER THE FACILITY. AFTER THE TRUCK ENTERED THE CUSTOMER SITE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT HAD BEGUN TO LEAK. THE CUSTOMER HAD THE DRIPS ON SITE CLEANED UP BY THEIR PERSONNEL AND DISPATCHED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT TO DEAL WITH THE SMALL SPILL ON BRADLEY. THE SMALL SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY THE HAZARDOUS INCIDENT RESPONSE TEAM (HLRT) OF SAN DIEGO COUNTY. OUR CONTACT WAS BRAD LONG. THEY INVESTIGATED HIS LAST TWO LAYOVER LOCATIONS AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ANY SPILL. INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER REVEALED THE SOURCE OF ISSUE VISUALLY. THE TRAILER WAS EMPTIED USING A PUMP TO ENSURE NEGATIVE PRESSURE AT THE CONNECTION AND MATERIAL WAS OFFLOADED IN CUSTOMER TANK. THE FLANGE WAS TIGHTENED ON SIGHT AND ALL MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND TRAILER RINSED PRIOR TO RETURN TRIP TO SHERWOOD, OREGON. THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE THE FAILURE OF THE WELL-PIPE SEAL. WHILE ON SITE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL TO THE BOLTS TO THIS FLANGE WERE INSUFFICIENTLY TORQUED. TIGHTENING THEM ONSITE WAS SUFFICIENT TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE. UPON IT'S RETURN, THE TRAILER WELL-PIPE CONNECTION WAS DISASSEMBLED AND DECONNED ALONG WITH THE BARREL OF THE TRAILER SO THAT IT COULD BE SERVICED. THERE WERE NO NOTABLE ISSUES WITH ANY OF THE SEALS BUT AS NOTED BY CASCADE AND POLAR SERVICE CENTER IN PORTLAND, OR, ALL OF THE BOLTS TO THE OTHER BOLTED FLANGES WERE LOOSE, SOME OF THEM TAKING TWO FULL TURNS TO SUFFICIENTLY TIGHTEN. SINCE THE TRAILER WAS PURCHASED AND PUT INTO SERVICE ONLY 8 MONTHS PRIOR THEN IT IS CONSIDERED TO BE EITHER A MANUFACTURING DEFECT, MAINTENANCE DEFECT OF BOTH.
column169: FIXED FLANGE CONNECTIONS ARE NOW ON A PERIODIC MAINTENANCE SCHEDULE. CCDC SUGGESTED A REVIEW OF TORQUE PROCEDURE AND GASKET MATERIALS BY AERO. AERO REVIEWED THE MATTER AND DECIDED THAT NO CORRECTIVE ACTIONS NEED TO BE TAKEN BY MANUFACTURER REPAIRS MADE BY TRUSTED LOCAL REPAIR FACILITY (POLAR).

column168: THERE IS NOT A VISIBLE GAUGE ON THE STORAGE TANK. THE CONSIGNEE TOLD THE DRIVER THE PRODUCT WOULD FIT IN THE STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER DISTRACTED WHILE PUMPING THE PRODUCT FORM THE CTMV TO THE STORAGE TANK. THE STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED, SPILLING ABOUT 500 GALLONS OF #1 DYED DIESEL INTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AROUND THE TANK. THE DRIVER DID NOT DISCOVER THE OVERFILL UNTIL HE EMPTIED THE CTMV COMPARTMENT, SO IT LIKELY FLOWED FOR A COUPLE OF MINUTES. THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF ANY TANK COMPONENT ON EITHER TANK; IT WAS SIMPLY OVERFILLED BY HUMAN ERROR. UPON DISCOVERING THE SPILL, THE DRIVER INITIATED RESPONSE AND CHECKED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS REMAINING IN CONTAINMENT. THE CONSIGNEE PUMPED THE PRODUCT FORM CONTAINMENT AND USED SORBENTS TO FINISH THE CLEANUP. PRODUCT AND USED SORBENTS WERE HELD FOR DISPOSAL BY EMERALD ENVIRONMENTAL.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: A.   PVS MINIBULK DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A DELIVERY TO CARSON COGENERATION IN CARSON CALIFORNIA WHEN HE WAS EXPOSED TO 66 DEGREE SULFURIC WHILE COMPLETING THE DELIVERY. A MECHANICAL EQUIPMENT FAILURE IN THE UPPER MANIFOLD OF THE AIR DIAPHRAGM PUMP OCCURRED WHILE BLOWING THE LINE CLEAR AND HE WAS EXPOSED TO A MOMENTARY RELEASE OF 93% SULFURIC ACID MIST. ACCORDING THE CUSTOMER, THE DRIVER WAS WEARING ALL OF HIS PPE, INCLUDING FACE SHIELD AND GOGGLES, AND WENT IMMEDIATELY INTO THE EWSS. EMT AND FIRE WERE CALLED AND HE REMAINED IN THE EWSS UNTIL THEY ARRIVED ON-SITE. HE HAS BEEN TAKEN VIA AMBULANCE TO HARBOR GENERAL IN CARSON, CA. NATE WAS BURNED AROUND HIS RIGHT EYE TOWARDS THE TEMPLE, HIS NECK AND A PORTION OF HIS RIGHT UPPER TORSO. HE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TRANSFERRED TO THE BURN UNIT AND HAS SINCE BEEN RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL. THE INITIAL VIEWING OF THE SECURITY CAMERA FOOTAGE SHOWS THE DRIVER STANDING BY THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE PUMP BOX AND THEN CROUCHING BY THE BOX AND REACHING INTO IT. THE VIDEO THEN SHOWS A MOMENTARY PRESSURE RELEASE OF ACID MIST ORIGINATING FROM THE, BOX: THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDS AROUND THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE, REMOVING A HARD HAT AND GLOVES AS HE RUNS TO THE SAFETY SHOWER LOCATED ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TRUCK, APPROXIMATELY 6 SECONDS ELAPSE BETWEEN THE EXPOSURE AND THE SHOWER ACTIVATION. BASED ON THE VIDEO EVIDENCE, THE DRIVER SPENT AT LEAST 13 MINUTES UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER. THE CUSTOMER REPORTS HE STAYED IN THE SHOWER UNTIL THE PARAMEDICS ARRIVED BUT THIS IS NOT SEEN ON THE FOOTAGE. PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE SCENE SHOW A MECHANICAL FAILURE OF THE PASSENGER SIDE 90 DEGREE END ON THE UPPER MANIFOLD OF THE ARO PUMP. THIS MECHANICAL FAILURE APPEARS TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE ACID VAPOR BLAST THAT HIT THE DRIVER. THE MIST RELEASE WAS STOPPED BY THE WALL FACING THE TRAILER AND RINSED TO CONTAINMENT ON SITE BY CUSTOMER.    B.     PVS Minibulk Driver was in the process of making a delivery to Carson Cogeneration in Carson California when he was exposed to 66 degree Sulfuric while completing the delivery. A mechanical equipment failure in the upper manifold of the air diaphragm pump occurred while blowing the line clear and he was exposed to a momentary release of 93% sulfuric acid mist.     According the customer, the driver was wearing all of his PPE, including face shield and goggles, and went immediately into the EWSS. EMT and Fire were called and he remained in the EWSS until they arrived on-site. He has been taken via ambulance to Harbor General in Carson, CA. Nate was burned around his right eye towards the temple, his neck and a portion of his right upper torso. He was subsequently transferred to the burn unit and has since been released from the hospital.     The initial viewing of the security camera footage shows the driver standing by the passenger side of the pump box and then crouching by the box and reaching into it. The video then shows a momentary pressure release of acid mist originating from the box. The
column169: A.  SINCE THE RELEASE APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN A RESULT OF OVER-PRESSURING THE PUMP USING AN UNREGULATED AIR SOURCE IN AN EFFORT TO BLOW IT CLEAR OF PRODUCT FOLLOWING THE DELIVERY OF MATERIAL. THIS PRACTICE HAS BEEN FORBIDDEN EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT AND COMMUNICATED TO ALL DRIVERS.   THE PUMP MATERIALS OF CONSTRUCTION ARE UNDER REVIEW TO DETERMINE IF A MORE SUITABLE DESIGN OR MATERIAL WOULD REDUCE OR ELIMINATE THE LIKELIHOOD OF REPEAT OCCURRENCE.   PUMP BOX DESIGN IS UNDER REVIEW TO DETERMINE THE FEASIBILITY RE-ORIENTING THE PUMP MOUNTING TO REDIRECT A POTENTIAL RELEASE OF MATERIAL WITHIN THE PUMP BOX RATHER THAN OUTSIDE IT. INSTALLING A SPLASH SHIELD OR SIMILAR ENGINEERING CONTROL AS A PROTECTIVE MEASURE ETC.    B.  Since the release appears to have been a result of over-pressuring the pump using an unregulated air source in an effort to blow it clear of product following the delivery of material.  This practice has been forbidden effective immediately following the incident and communicated to all drivers.     The pump materials of construction are under review to determine if a more suitable design or material would reduce or eliminate the likelihood of repeat occurrence.     Pump box design is under review to determine the feasibility re-orienting the pump mounting to redirect a potential release of material within the pump box rather than outside it, installing a splash-shield or similar engineering control as a protective measure, etc.

ON DECEMBER 22 2015 A PETERSON OIL CO DRIVER TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON STATE HIGHWAY AE, A NARROW HILLY CURVY TWO LAND ROAD WITHOUT SHOULDERS HAD AN ACCIDENT CAUSING A DAMAGE TO PERTERSON OIL CO. EQUIPMENT. WHILE GOING DOWN A DECLINE WITH A CURVE TO THE LEFT (PICTURE1) THE VEHICLES RIGHT FRONT TIRE LEFT THE PAVEMENT. THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAD RECENTLY ADDED SOME AGGREGATE TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE CURVE IN AN ATTEMPT TO ALLEVIATE A SHARP "BREAK" FROM THE PAVEMENT TO THE DITCH. THIS MATERIAL WAS NOT COMPACTED. THE TRANSITION AREA AND DITCH WERE VERY SOFT AS A RESULT OF RECENT RECORD SETTING RAINS. BECAUSE OF THE STEEP ANGEL AND SOFTNESS OF THE DITCH, THE DRIVER HAD NO CHOICE BUT TO ATTEMPT TO REGAIN THE PAVEMENT. IN DOING SO, THE VEHICLE REGAINED THE ROADWAY AT AN ACUTE ANGLE, CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL. THE VEHICLE THEN OVERTURNED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, SLIDING ACROSS THE ROAD AND ENTERING THE OPPOSITE DITCH REAR END FIRST. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST AS SHOWN IN PICTURE 2.   THE DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE AND CALLED PETERSON OIL COS. OFFICE. OFFICE PERSONNEL CALLED 911 WITH A DESCRIPTION AND APPROXIMATE LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT. AFTER CALLING 911, OFFICE PERSONNEL THEN CALLED PETERSON OIL CO MANAGEMENT. PETERSON OIL CO MANAGEMENT AND SULLIVAN FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE NEAR THE SAME TIME. AS THE VEHICLE WAS LEAKING LPG VAPORS, IT WAS DECIDED TO BLOCK THE ROADWAY AT A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN BY PRIVATE VEHICLE TO MISSOURI BAPTIST HOSPITAL TO BE EXAMINED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. HE FOUND TO HAVE SUFFERED NO INJURIES.   IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WHEN THE VEHICLE SLID BACKWARDS INTO THE DITCH A 3/4 INCH PIPE NIPPLE CONNECTING THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE (THREADED INTO THE TANK) AND THE 3/4 INCH HAND WHEEL GLOBE VALVE HAD BEEN BENT AND CRACKED. SEE PICTURE 3. THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE, A REGO A32726 RATED AT 20 GPM LPG/ 10 GPM NH3 INITIALLY DID NOT CLOSE, ALLOWING LIQUID AND VAPOR LPG TO LEAK FROM THE TANK.    AFTER LEAKING FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE SHUT STOPPING THE LEAK. IT IS UNKNOWN EXACTLY WHY THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE FAILED TO INITIALLY CLOSE OR WHY IT CLOSED LATER. IT IS THEORIZED THAT CRACK IN THE PIPING NIPPLE DID NOT INITIALLY ALLOW SUFFICIENT ESCAPING LPG LIQUID PHASE FLOW TO CLOSE THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE. AS THE LIQUID LPG LEVEL IN THE TANK DECREASED MORE VAPOR PHASE LPG WAS RELEASED. EVENTUALLY THE VAPOR PHASE FLOW EXCEEDED THE FLOW RATE OF THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE AND IT SHUT. THE VEHICLE WAS THEN TOWED TO PETERSON OIL CO'S PLANT. AT PETERSON OIL'S PLANT, THE REMAINING LPG WAS PUMPED FROM THE TANK.   NO MITIGATION WAS REQUIRED AS THE LPG VAPORIZED WITHOUT ANY FURTHER DAMAGES. SEE ATTACHED REPORT FROM THE SULLIVAN FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT.    PHOTO ATTACHED
column169: IT APPEARS, TO THE BEST OF PETERSON OIL CO KNOWLEDGE, THAT NO ACTIONS ARE NECESSARY CONCERNING THE EQUIPMENT FACING TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. A WRECK, CAUSING DAMAGE TO AN EXCESS FLOW VALVE, CONTRIBUTED TO THE LEAK OF LPG FROM PETERSON OIL CO EQUIPMENT. WHILE NO EVIDENCE OF NEGLECT OR WRONGDOING WAS FOUND BY PETERSON OIL CO OR THE DRIVER, PETERSON OIL CO FINDS ITS DRIVERS SAFETY AND THE SAFETY OF OTHERS ON THE ROAD TO BE OF PARAMOUNT IMPORTANCE. IN ORDER TO PREVENT POSSIBLY RECURRENCE OF ANY TYPE OF ACCIDENT, PETERSON OIL CO TOOK SEVERAL DIFFERENT APPROACHES, IN OUR BEST ATTEMPT, TO PREVENT POSSIBLY RECURRENCE OF A DRIVER ACCIDENT. IN AN ATTEMPT TO ENSURE THE MOST CAPABLE DRIVING, THE DRIVER INVOLVED WAS TEMPORARILY FORCED INTO A PASSENGER POSITION WHEN RETURNING TO WORK AT PETERSON OIL CO. THE DRIVER, HAVING BI-WEEKLY MEETINGS WITH PETERSON OIL CO MANAGEMENT, WAS ASKED TO GIVE HONEST FEEDBACK ON HIS READINESS TO RETURN AS DRIVER OF PETERSON OIL CO EQUIPMENT. A MORE SENIOR EMPLOYEE WAS THEN ASSIGNED AS A PASSENGER AND THEN ASKED TO REPORT ON DRIVING CONDITIONS AND HABITS OF INVOLVED DRIVER. THE REPORTS FOUND NORMAL, SAFE DRIVING HABITS. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NORMAL HUMAN ERROR CONTRIBUTED TO WRECK. IN A FURTHER ATTEMPT TO ENSURE ALL DRIVERS SAFETY PETERSON OIL CO IS CURRENTLY WORKING WITH IT INSURANCE COMPANY TO PROVIDE TRAINING AND INCREASE THE NUMBER OF SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: OUR TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING EAST ON US 280. THE DRIVER OF A PICKUP TRUCK PULLING A TRAILER LOADED WITH SWEET POTATOES TRAVELING ON ODENS MILL RD. STOPPED IN THE INTERSECTION BLOCKING BOTH LANES OF 280 EAST OUR TRANSPORT STRUCK THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRAILER WHICH LOCKED THE STEERING OF OUR TRANSPORT. THE TRANSPORT SKIDDED TOWARDS DRIVER'S SIDE TURNED OVER TOWARDS PASSENGER SIDE; COMING TO REST DIRECTLY ON ITS TOP PARTIALLY IN WEST BOUND LEFT TURN LANE, PARTIALLY IN MEDIAN. THE CRASH CAUSED A CRACK NEAR TOP FRONT OF THE TANKER FROM WHICH FUEL WAS LEAKING. OAK GROVE FIRE AND RESCUE RESPONDED ALSO SYLACAUGA FIRE DEPT. THOSE DEPT STOPPED THE LEAKING OF FUEL. AL STATE TROOPER RESPONDED TO INVESTIGATE AND MANAGE TRAFFIC, ALSO TALLADEGA COUNTY SHERIFFS RESPONDED MANAGING TRAFFIC. FIRE DEPT DEPLOYED FOAM TO PREVENT IGNITION OF FUEL. WE REQUESTED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE COME AND COLLECT SPILLED FUEL FROM THE MEDIAN AND DO REMEDIAL WORK IE REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATE SOIL AND REPLACEMENT AND RESTORATION OF MEDIAN. WE TRANSFERRED UN SPILLED FUEL TO ANOTHER TRANSPORT AND COMPLETED DELIVERY.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT CAN BE TOTALLY ATTRIBUTED TO UNWISE ACTION ON PART OF DRIVER OF THE PICK UP PULLING TRAILER LOAD OF POTATOES; TROOPERS REPORT INDICATED FAILURE TO YIELD RIGHT OF WAY BY SIDE DRIVER. THERE WAS NOTHING LACKING RELATED TO OUR EQUIPMENT OR ACTION ON PART OF OUR DRIVER IRONICALLY OUR COMPANY HAD RECENTLY HELD OUR PERIODIC SAFETY MEETING WHICH FEATURED A DVD CONCERTING ROLLOVERS. AS FAR AS WE CAN ASCERTAIN THERE WAS NOTHING WE COULD HAVE DONE OR CAN DO TO PREVENT ACTION ON THE PART OF OTHERS SUCH AS THIS INCIDENT.

column168: LOTT DRIVER WAS HEADING EAST ON US 84 WHEN HIS TRAILER TIRE LEFT THE SHOULDER, HE OVER CORRECTED AND ROLLED THE 18 WHEELER LOADED W/DIESEL. HE WAS UNINJURED, BUT VEHICLE WAS TOTALED. column169: IN THAT DRIVER WS CITED FOR CARELESS OPERATION. MORE TRAINING AND SUPERVISOR IS OUR PRIMARY GOAL. THE TRUCK, TRAILERS AND EQUIPMENT OPERATED AS WELL AS CAN EXPECT USE THE CIRCUMSTANCE. HUMAN ERROR AND CARELESSNESS LACK OF TOTAL FOCUS REMAINS A CAUSE OF CONCERN AND THAT WE STRIVE TO REDUCE THOUGHT OUR HIRING AND TRAINING EFFORTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADED HEADED TO DESTINATION, WEATHER WAS A WET AND WINDY STORM BLOWING IN FROM THE PACIFIC, DRIVER CAME AROUND A RIGHT HAND TURN IN A RECOMMENDED 30 (I THINK) CORNER, FROM THERE IT ENTERS INTO A LEFT HAND 30 CORNER, AT WHICH TIME HE NOTED THAT THE TRAILER WAS SLIDING TO THE TURN OUT, WHERE HE BEGAN TO BRAKE, THE TRAILER SLIDE TO THE TURN OUT WHERE THERE WAS A 4" DROP FROM THE PAVEMENT TO GRAVEL TURN OUT. THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO BRAKE AS THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK TRAILER SLOSHED IT OVER ON ITS SIDE.     THE ROLL OVER BAR WHERE THE TANK FAILED AS IT HAD A TEAR IN IT THE VAPOR RECOVERY PODS ON THE TOP COULD NOT HOLD THE PRESSURE AND ALLOW THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE TANK TRAILER.     THE RELEASING CONTINUED UNTIL PRODUCT LEVEL DROPPED BELOW THE VAPOR PODS.     PERSONAL CALL FROM THE CAL FIRE RESPONDED WITH PADS AND SOME ABSORBENT BOOM, THEY ESTIMATED THE LOSS AT A MUCH SMALLER VOLUME, AS I THINK MOST CAME OUT IN THE BEGINNING BEFORE THEIR ARRIVAL. MORE ABSORBENT EQUIPMENT WAS DISPATCHED FROM THE CARRIER'S SUPPLY AND APPLIED TO THE SPILL. WEATHER CONDITIONS INHIBITED INITIAL WORK AND WHEN THE TRAILER WAS UP RIGHT ONLY A CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS LEFT AT THE SITE, SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO A DITCH AND MARCH, WHICH BY CULVERT FLOWED INTO BIG LAGOON. THE FOLLOWING DAY MORE RESPONSE WAS CONTACTED WHERE A HARD BOOM AND SOFT BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED IN THE LAGOON. WITH THE SENSITIVE MARCH LAND AND ECO-SYSTEM WITH IN REDWOOD NATIONAL PARK, EQUIPMENT WAS NOT ENCOURAGED. CLEAN UP IS BEING BASED ON HAD WORK AND DISPOSAL.
column169: WET WINDY CURVY ROAD, MEETINGS CONDUCTED WITH FULL DRIVE STAFF. TANK MANUFACTURING WAS CONTACTED TO DETERMINE IF THE TRAILER WAS LOADED PROPERLY, AND WE HAD MADE ADJUSTMENTS WITH OUR LOADING QUANTITIES.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: TWO 100 LB PROPANE TANKS WERE PICKED UP FROM A CUSTOMER IN CORONA, CA AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR PLANT IN A PICKUP TRUCK TO BLOOMINGTON, CA BECAUSE THEY HAD BEEN OVERFILLED AND WERE HEAVIER THAN USUAL. WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE PLANT, I TURNED THE TRUCK OFF, THEN IMMEDIATELY BEGAN EVACUATING PROPANE FROM THE TANKS IN THE BACK OF THE PICKUP TRUCK. I LEFT THE TANKS IN THE TRUCK AND WALKED OVER TO OUR STORAGE AREA TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANY OTHER TANKS I COULD TAKE IN PLACE OF THE ONES THAT WERE BEING EVACUATED. I DO NOT KNOW EXACTLY HOW LONG I WALKED AWAY FOR, BUT WOULD ESTIMATE IT WAS LESS THAN TWO MINUTES. WHEN I TURNED AROUND, THERE WAS A LARGE FIRE IN THE BACK OF THE PICKUP TRUCK. I GRABBED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND RAN TOWARDS THE TRUCK AND BEGAN TRYING TO PUT THE FIRE OUT FOR A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF TIME AS I REALIZED THE FIRE WAS TOO BIG AND THE TANKS WERE GOING TO EXPLODE. I RAN DOWN THE HILL AT THE PLANT AND TIRED TO GET OUT OF THE GATE, BUT IT WAS LOCKED AND MY GATE OPENER WAS IN THE TRUCK THAT WAS ON FIRE. THE TANKS BOTH EXPLODED AT DIFFERENT TIME. I DO NOT KNOW HOW LONG IT WAS IN BETWEEN EXPLOSIONS OR HOW LONG IT TOOK FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ARRIVE. ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID ARRIVE, I EVACUATED THE PLANT AND THEY PUT THE BURNING PICKUP TRUCK OUT. I WAS THE ONLY EMPLOYEE/ PERSON ON SITE THAT NIGHT AS IT WAS AFTER HOURS AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
column169: ENCORE PROPANE LIQUEFIED PROPANE GAS  EVACUATION PROCEDURES    BEFORE YOU START ANY TRANSFER PROCESS, IT IS IMPORTANT THAT YOU MAKE SURE YOU ARE WORKING IN A SAFE ENVIRONMENT AND THAT YOU ARE FULLY PROTECTED. MAKE SURE YOU ARE AWARE OF SAFE TRANSFER PROCEDURES AS WELL AS ALL THE TANK VALVES AND TRANSFER EQUIPMENT TO BE USED. BE AWARE OF THE MANUFACTURE'S INSTRUCTIONS FOR ALL EQUIPMENT TO BE USED. SPECIAL CARE IS REQUIRED WITH ANGLE VALVES TO ENSURE THAT THEY DO NOT DIRECT LIQUID TOWARD PEOPLE OR IGNITION SOURCES. WHEN TRANSFERRING LIQUID PROPANE BETWEEN CONTAINERS THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA SHOULD BE OBSERVED    ALL SOURCES OF IGNITION WITHIN 25 FEET OF THE POINT OF TRANSFER MUST BE REMOVED, EXTINGUISHED, OR TURNED OFF FOR THE DURATION OF THE OPERATION.     INTERNAL COMBUSTION ENGINES WITHIN 15 FEET OF THE POINT OF TRANSFER MUST BE SHUT DOWN WHILE TRANSFER OPERATIONS ARE IN PROGRESS, EXPECT FOR ENGINES ON TRANSFER EQUIPMENT AND OTHERS AS LISTED IN NFPA 58    AT LEAST ONE RECENTLY INSPECTED FIRE EXTINGUISHER, HAVING A MINIMUM CAPACITY OF 18 LB. DRY CHEMICAL WITH A B C OR A B C RATING MUST BE WITHIN EASY REACH DURING THE ENTIRE OPERATION.     A QUALIFIED INDIVIDUAL MUST BE PRESENT AT THE OPERATION DURING THE ENTIRE EVALUATION PROCEDURE.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE THE DRIVER MISCALCULATED THE AVAILABLE SPACE IN THE CUSTOMER'S TANK AND HIS LOAD DID NOT FIT. THE WEATHER THAT DAY WAS 35 DEGREES AND RAINY WITH 35MPH WINDS. THE DRIVER STARTED HIS PUMP AND GOT IN HIS CAB AND WAITED FOR THE TRAILER TO GO EMPTY. I ESTIMATE THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE AT 15 MINUTES. WE WERE ON SCENE WITHIN 45 MINUTES OF THE RELEASE WITH A PUMP TRUCK, A BACKHOE, AND SIX MEN, AND IMMEDIATELY BEGAN CLEAN UP.THIS INCIDENT WAS COMPLETELY ATTRIBUTABLE TO HUMAN ERROR. THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE OF ANY KIND INVOLVED.

column168: AT ROUGHLY 0130 ON 12-2-15. ONE OF OUR DRIVERS WHO WORKS IN THE UPRR NORTHLAKE RAILYARD, WAS GOING TO FILL COUPLE LOCOMOTIVES. OUR DRIVER WENT OVER A RR CROSSING AND AS HE DID, THE MUD FLAP ON OUR TRACTOR TRAILER SET GOT CAUGHT UP IN THE CROSSING. MUD FLAP BRACKET FROM THE TRACTOR POKED A SMALL ¼ HOLE (SIZE OF THE BRACKET BAR) INTO OUR TRAILER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TURNED UNIT AROUND AND DROVE BACK  TO THE LOADING / OFF LOAD PAD WHICH HAS CONTAINMENT IN PLACE. HE OFF LOADED THE TRAILER. AS DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE HEADING BACK TO THE OFF LOAD PAD, APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED.  WE CALLED COMPANY OUT TO PLACE ABSORBENT PADS DOWN WHERE THE RELEASE OCCURRED. WE BROUGHT SAND IN AND PLACED IT ON SURFACE ROAD/ PATH TO LOAD PAD. WE THEN PICKED UP AND REMOVED FROM PROPERTY ALL THE SAND WE PUT DOWN, AND LASTLY WE BROUGHT STONE IN AND REPLACED BY THE CROSSING WERE INCIDENT OCCURRED. IF YOU HAVE ANY OTHER QUESTIONS PLEASE LET ME KNOW.

MANUEL CASTILLO WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON NM 68 AT APPROXIMATELY 05:00AM. MANUEL STATED HE HAD A BLOW OUT OR A TIRE GO FLAT ON THE RIGHT FRONT STEER TIRE OF THE TRUCK. THIS CAUSED THE TRUCK TO SHIFT AND PULL TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY. DRIVER ADVISED HE BRAKED AND ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN CONTROL THE VEHICLE BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. MANUEL ADVISED HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE COMING TO REST ON THE NORTH SIDE SHOULDER AS WELL AS IN THE TRAFFIC LANES. THE DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE, AND SAW THAT THERE WAS FUEL LEAKING FROM THE TANK TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND. HE IMMEDIATELY REMOVED HIMSELF FROM THE AREA AND STOPPED AN ONCOMING VEHICLE THAT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND, AT THIS POINT, MANUEL ADVISED THE LEAKING FUEL IGNITED. THE DRIVER OF THE STOPPED VEHICLE, CALLED 911. POLICE AND FIRE WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SEEN. EMERGENCY SERVICES ARRIVED ON SEEN AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION. ADVANCED CHEMICAL TRANSPORT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SEEN TO HANDLE THE REMOVAL OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER AS WELL AS THE INITIAL CLEANUP. NM 68 REMAINED CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS UNTIL LATE IN THE DAY.
column169: CONTINUED FOCUS ON SAFETY.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: AFTER PASSING LAKE STREET OFF RAMP I WAS BEHIND A FLATBED SEMI TRAILER THAT WAS LOADED WITH SOME SORT OF MATERIEL STRAPPED DOWN. I SAW A PIECE OF WHAT LOOKED LIKE ANGLE IRON COME OFF THE UNIT AND BOUNCE IN MY LANE. I WAS ABLE TO AVOID HITTING IT WAS THE STEER TIRES WITH A SLIGHT ADJUSTMENT. I HAD CARS IN THE NEXT LANE ON DRIVERS SIDE AND FREEWAY SHOULDER ON PASSENGER SIDE. I DIDN'T WANT TO MAKE ANY AGGRESSIVE MOVEMENTS AS I WAS LOADED. I FELT THE METAL HIT THE UNDERNEATH OF MY TRACTOR. MAYBE HITTING THE DRIVER LINE AS I HEARD A THUMP AND FELT A SHOCK IN THE CAB OF MY TRUCK. I CHECKED MY MIRRORS ON BOTH SIDES IMMEDIATELY. AFTER A FEW SECONDS I NOTICED MY TIRES ON PASSENGER SIDE OF TRAILER COMING APART. I SAW HUNKS OF AT LEAST ONE TIRE FLYING APART. I IMMEDIATELY SLOWED AND LOOKED FOR A SAFE PLACE TO GET OFF THE FREEWAY. FORTUNATELY, THERE WAS AN AREA DIRECTLY AHEAD THAT ALLOWED FOR ME TO GET OUT OF THE TRAFFIC AREA. I STOPPED THE UNIT AND PUT ON MY EMERGENCY FLASHERS AND WENT TO INSPECT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. I WENT TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WHEN I SAW SMOKE COMING FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER. I RAN BACK AND GOT MY FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND RETURNED TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. I SAW ONE TIRE ON FIRE AND THE OTHER ONE BLOWN OUT. THE TIRE THAT CAME APART HAD APPEARED TO HAVE SOME OF IT WRAPPED AROUND THE AXLE AND WAS ON FIRE. I ASKED AN AMBULANCE CREW THAT HAD STOPPED TO CALL 911 AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PROCEEDED TO DO MY BEST TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. I EVENTUALLY USED UP ALL MY FIRE EXTINGUISHERS (2) AND WAS NOT ABLE TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. IT SEEMED LIKE IT TOOK FOREVER FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ARRIVE. MAYBE 10 OR 12 MINUTES AND WHEN THEY GOT THERE THEY SAID IT WAS SAFER TO GET EVERYONE AWAY AND LET IT BURN. I SUGGESTED HITTING IT WITH WATER TO PUT THE FIRE OUT BUT THEY SAID "THE POLICY WAS TO STAY BACK". FINALLY AFTER ABOUT 4 HOURS THEY SPRAYED UNIT WITH FOAM AND PUT OUT THE LAST OF THE FIRE. I GAVE REPORTS TO THE CHP AND FIRE DEPARTMENT ON SCENE. NO OTHER PARTIES WERE INVOLVED AND NO PRODUCT SPILLED FORM THE TRAILER. IT WAS A TERRIBLE FEELING TO SEE MY NEW TRUCK AND TRAILER TO BURN DOWN TO NOTHING.
